theme_map_sixtysix <- function(){ 
  ggthemes::theme_map() %+replace%
    theme(
      text = ggthemes::theme_fivethirtyeight()$text,
      title = ggthemes::theme_fivethirtyeight()$plot.title,
      panel.grid.major = element_line(color="grey90")
    )
}

    geom_sf(
    color = sixtysix_colors$light_red,
    size=2,

  ) +

    ),

  ) +

We have two types of transformations to make. Some divisions from 2016 get split up into multiple 2019 divisions: 2016’s division 21 becomes 21, 33, and 34. Also, parts of some 2016 divisions get combined to form new ones: the new division 10 consists of paste of 2016 10 and 26.

Crosswalking values is usually done pretty simply: we take the counts from the 2016 data, and apportion them to 2019 boundaries. Usually, we do this by calculating the area of the intersection (“areal weighting”):

st_intersection(
  divs_16 %>% filter(warddiv16 == "0521"), 
  divs_19
) %>% 
  mutate(area = st_area(geometry)) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  select(warddiv16, warddiv19, area) %>% 
  group_by() %>% 
  mutate(prop_of_16 = as.numeric(area / sum(area)))
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
##   warddiv16 warddiv19             area   prop_of_16
##      <fctr>    <fctr>      <S3: units>        <dbl>
## 1      0521      1802     66.16341 m^2 6.830745e-05
## 2      0521      0530    918.91200 m^2 9.486896e-04
## 3      0521      0534 676270.02908 m^2 6.981847e-01
## 4      0521      0533 179224.47653 m^2 1.850323e-01
## 5      0521      0521 112132.32843 m^2 1.157660e-01

The above shows us that Division 05-21 in 2016 was split up into five divisions for 2019. Two of them–1802 and 0530–look like noise; the areas are tiny and probably represent a trivial move in the boundary.

To apportion 2016’s votes to 2019 boundaries, we would give new division 05-34 69.8% of the votes, 05-33 18.5%, and 05-21 11.6%. Done.

Exercise: What assumptions make this apportionment valid?
